This paper is about identifying agreement and disagreement in social media dialogue, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). The most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language), which focuses on NLP and its applications. The paper also involves machine learning and data mining, which are relevant to sub-categories such as cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.SD (Sound and Music Computing). Additionally, the paper deals with theoretical accounts of dialogue, which could be relevant to sub-categories such as cs.CY (Computers and Society) and cs.LG (Machine Learning).
